{"id":"1811.09430","submitter":"Bj\\\"orn Gustafsson","authors":"Bj\\\"orn Gustafsson","title":"Vortex motion and geometric function theory: the role of connections","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We formulate the equations for point vortex dynamics on a closed two\ndimensional Riemann manifold in the language of affine and other kinds of\nconnections. The speed of a vortex is then expressed in terms of the difference\nbetween an affine connection derived from the coordinate Robin function and the\nLevi-Civita connection associated to the Riemannian metric.\n  A Hamiltonian formulation of the same dynamics is also given. The relevant\nHamiltonian function consists of two main terms. One of the terms is the\nwell-known quadratic form based on a matrix whose entries are Green and Robin\nfunctions, while the other term describes the energy contribution from those\ncirculating flows which are not implicit in the Green functions. One main issue\nof the paper is the clarification of the somewhat intricate exchanges of energy\nbetween these two terms of the Hamiltonian.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 23 Nov 2018 11:15:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-11-26"}
